  8 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1435820400,
    'title' => 'Five Rude Emails You Send Every Day',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/5727685273755737983',
    'link2' => '2015/07/five-rude-emails-you-send-every-day',
    'article' => '<p>It is so easy to be misunderstood on email - and even if you are the most likeable and well behaved person in the world, you can still come across offensive.</p>
<p>In an email there is no emotion, facial expression, tone of voice, gestures, postures or any other visual or audible clues to help people interpret what you mean.</p>
<p>Email is very efficient and convenient, allowing conversations to progress at the pace of each person as and when they have a moment to reply. However, without the conversational clues people pick up on during a conversation, there are many pitfalls that can easily lead to misunderstandings.</p>
<p>Here are some of those pitfalls that you might want to look out for - and hopefully avoid.</p>
<h3>Carbon Copies and Reply to All</h3>
<p>Copying other people into an email that is really only meant for one recipient can be annoying - not only for the copied recipients who don\'t really want to "hear" what you have to say, as it\'s not relevant to them, but potentially also for the actual recipient, who may feel that you want to ridicule them in front of others.</p>
<p>On the flipside, if you receive an email from someone where a whole group of people is copied in, you don\'t need to reply to everyone just to say "thank you" or "understood". That sort of response should simply go back to the original sender - the others are unlikely to need to see your reply.</p>
<p>Only reply to everyone if you\'re adding to the conversation, asking additional questions or are presenting another point that the rest of the group needs to see so they can discuss it or so that they are made aware of the additional information.</p>
<h3>One Word Answers</h3>
<p>Some people write very long emails, but others take to the other extreme. Most people don\'t use one word answers when they are face to face with someone - or when they do, they usually come across as short and rude.</p>
<p>The same is true for emails. Keep it brief, if you want to make the email exchange efficient, but stick to whole sentences and try to match your length of reply to the original email. If someone has spent a long time putting together a detailed email, it would be very rude to reply with a simple "agreed".</p>
<p>If you don\'t have time to write a long answer, then at least say so in your reply. Most people with understand that you can\'t write a long reply if you\'re busy, but unless you tell them that you\'re busy, the recipient won\'t know.</p>
<h3>Everything is URGENT</h3>
<p>In today\'s work environment, and especially with electronic communication, everyone has come to expect an instant answer and an immediate solution to a problem. So to stand out from the rest, it\'s so tempting to title your emails "URGENT" or "ASAP".</p>
<p>However, as mentioned above, an email exchange is about allowing the recipient to reply as and when they have time. The expectation of an immediate response is misplaced.</p>
<p>If something is really so urgent and needs immediate attention, then pick up the phone or get up and go and see the person at their desk. That way you can assess how busy the other person is and if there are, more important (and "more urgent") issues to be dealt with, before your problem can be addressed.</p>
<p>If you send an email about an urgent issue and don\'t get a response, because the other person is busy, you only end up calling or seeing them anyway - so why waste the time to compose and send an email.</p>
<p>If the issue isn\'t actually urgent, then why pretend in your email that it is?</p>
<h3>Everyone Else is Wrong</h3>
<p>Criticising is always easy. Coming up with a better solution is much, much harder. Also, hindsight is a brilliant thing - so telling someone how they could have avoided a problem after the event is usually not very helpful. Chances are the other person already knows.</p>
<p>If you want to offer constructive criticism, you need to explain how something could have been differently to improve the outcome - rather than explain what someone shouldn\'t have done.</p>
<p>Also don\'t just offer your criticism - however well meant. It\'s usually best to wait to be asked before providing your thoughts.</p>
<h3>Straight to the Point</h3>
<p>Doing away with pleasantries can feel like a good way of not wasting the recipient\'s time, but many people prefer a quick "introduction" before getting to the point of the email. It doesn\'t have to turn into a long exchange about the recipient\'s life story, but a simple "how is it going?" will soften the email.</p>
<p>If you know you\'re asking for a big favour or are potentially putting the recipient under additional pressure with your request, then it\'s always best to lead in with that. If you acknowledge that you\'re asking the recipient to go the extra mile, you\'re more likely to be received well and the recipient doesn\'t think you unfeeling. We all would like to feel others around understand our constraints, so it\'s better to acknowledge them.</p>
<h3>Email Pitfalls Avoided</h3>
<p>Following the simple advice above should help you avoid the usual email pitfalls. Emails are a great tool, but they can make the conversation a lot more impersonal and dehumanize the recipient - so take an extra few seconds and think about who you\'re sending the email to.</p>
<p>If you need some additional advice on emails, or any other IT or computer issues, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a>.</p>',
    'labels' => 'advice, business, emails',
  ),
  9 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1435215600,
    'title' => 'Do you have a disaster recovery plan?',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/729247451943689028',
    'link2' => '2015/06/do-you-have-disaster-recovery-plan',
    'article' => '<p>Very often you are not remembered by your successes, but by your failures and how well you dealt with them. One failure that more often than not force a business to fold is not being able to recover from a disaster quickly or even at all.</p>
<p>Disaster in this context isn\'t necessarily of the natural kind. It is more often the failure of your technology and the subsequent loss of data, connectivity and general ability to do business. If you haven\'t planned for the worst, you will find it hard to bring your business back up and running.</p>
<p>Businesses give various reasons for not having a disaster recovery plan. Cost, both in time and actual financial terms, buy-in from management and/or staff, or the complexity of implementing and testing the plan.</p>
<p>However, cost is usually a secondary factor. If you can quantify how much you would lose in terms of potential business if the worst happened, you already have a figure you can incorporate in your plan and which gives you an idea of the sort of investment needed.</p>
<p>Complexity is a real concern, but like with so many things, starting with a high level overview and breaking everything down little by little will easily deal with the potential complexity that is involved.</p>
<p>Buy-in should easily be dealt with - after all, if the worst happens and you have assigned a figure to how much business could be lost, both management and staff will quickly see the risk to the business and their own livelihoods.</p>
<p>The last thing is testing of course. Once you have put together your recovery plan, it\'s time to test it. The testing can be difficult, depending on your scenario, but if you identify a time when your business would be least impacted, you should be able to simulate a real life disaster and then see if your plan can cope with it.</p>
<p>Of course, once the plan has been put together and successfully tested, it needs to be kept up-to-date and tested regularly. An out-of-date plan is no good to anyone - even though it is still better than no plan at all.</p>
<p>If you need help with disaster recovery planning, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a> for free advice.</p>',
    'labels' => 'advice, business, disaster, DR, protection',
  ),
