  array (
    'published' => 1434610800,
    'title' => 'WordPress is very popular but also vulnerable to attacks',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/422261172260635755',
    'link2' => '2015/06/wordpress-is-very-popular-but-also',
    'article' => '<p>A couple of months ago Wordpress issued an update and "strongly encouraged" all of their customers to install it "immediately". As you can probably tell from the language used, the update addressed a serious flaw in the highly popular CMS (content management system).</p>
<p>Wordpress is used by nearly 50% of websites worldwide, so a single vulnerability found in Wordpress gives hackers the potential to quickly and easily attack a huge pool of websites.</p>
<p>The technical details of the vulnerabilities plugged by the Wordpress update are at best boring to non-technical people, at worst non-technical people running their own Wordpress sites will ignore or not even be aware when they need to apply updates to keep their websites safe.</p>
<p>It is always best to let experts deal with your website, but Wordpress has the reputation that anyone and everyone can use it - and unfortunately that is not the case.</p>
<p>The good news is that Wordpress has not only fixed the vulnerabilities, but also made the CMS generally more robust. So if you are non-technical and have your own Wordpress site, you may feel safer.</p>
<p>Yet, it is still highly recommended to leave the maintenance of your Wordpress site to someone who knows what they do - so that you can focus on the sites content.</p>
<p>If you want advice on where best to host your Wordpress site to ensure it\'s always up-to-date, or to find out about alternatives to Wordpress and how to move your site to those other solutions, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a>.</p>',
    'labels' => 'CMS, security, support, Wordpress',
  ),
  11 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1434006000,
    'title' => 'Never trust default passwords',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/8864921860954471354',
    'link2' => '2015/06/never-trust-default-passwords',
    'article' => '<p>A lot of the devices and services you use every day are set up with a default password - often printed on the box the device came in, or in an email in the case of online services. The password is often very complicated, so on the face of it there should be no need to change it. After all, who would guess a 20 character password that is a random of letters, digits and punctuation?</p>
<p>Unfortunately the problem is not whether the password is complicated. The issue is that a lot of vendors set the same password on all of the devices they send out. That means that if you know the password for your device or service, you can use it to get access to someone else who has the same device or service.</p>
<p>Luckily, more and more vendors and service providers now create a different password every time a device is sent out or a new account is created. In fact, often you have to set your own password the first time you access the device or service.</p>
<p>The practice of changing the password yourself is something that should always be done - whether the device or your service provider ask for it or not. It is the only way to ensure that nobody knows your password - and of course make sure your password is complex.</p>
<p>If you need help with how to introduce good password policies and what tools are available to make dealing with strong passwords easier, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a>.</p>',
    'labels' => 'default, devices, passwords, protection, security, services',
  ),
  12 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1433401200,
    'title' => 'What happens with stolen personal data?',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/2087026602027459753',
    'link2' => '2015/06/what-happens-with-stolen-personal-data',
    'article' => '<p>In a recent experiment security vendor BitGlass created an Excel file with several thousand made up social security numbers, credit card details, names and email addresses and put it on the so-called "Dark Web".</p>
<p>They found that within 12 days the data had been opened nearly 1,100 times in more than 22 different countries in five continents. The first time someone opened the Excel file, which contained special code to record location information each time it was accessed, was within a few days of having been uploaded.</p>
<p>It may come as no surprise that the file was mainly opened by users in Nigeria, Russia, and Brazil, with the most activity coming from Nigeria and Russia. On the other hand, the fact that the fake details were cross-checked and compared with other stolen data is new. One set of the fake credit card details was used to make a purchase, clearly in an attempt to test if the information was valid or not.</p>
<p>The experiment clearly showed how easy it was to distribute stolen information on the Dark Web, so it is still vital that everyone keeps personal information secure and safe.</p>
<p>If you want advice on securing your and your customers\' data and general digital safety advice, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a>.</p>',
    'labels' => 'Dark Web, identify theft, protection, security',
  ),
  13 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1432796400,
    'title' => 'Does your website portray your business in a good light?',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/2576636739809744717',
    'link2' => '2015/05/does-your-website-portray-your-business',
    'article' => '<p>A business website is an opportunity for your business to start a conversation about you, your business and your products with potential customers and to show them that your business is professional, credible, trustworthy and ethical. Your website should contain pertinent copy, facts, informational tips and testimonials to really put your business in a positive light.</p>
<p>The Internet of 5 or 10 years ago is gone. Just slapping a website up to say you have one is not only completely ineffective - and if you haven\'t updated it or made it accessible to the ever growing number of smart phone and tablet users, your business is not going to benefit.</p>
<p>Many studies show that around 80% of consumers looking to purchase goods or services are going online to seek them out. Their buying decision will be based on the information they find, either on your website or your competitors\'. 73% of those consumers will make a buying decision then and there, based on what they read or see, so ensuring they see your website and not your competitors\' and that they can complete their purchase with you and not someone else becomes highly important.</p>
<p>So make sure you have an up-to-date website with relevant content and that potential customers can easily find via search engines and your business will increase.</p>
<p>For advice on marketing your business effectively to your potential customers, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a>.</p>',
    'labels' => 'advantages, business, services, websites',
  ),
  14 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1432191600,
    'title' => 'What your business can learn from Cirque du Soleil',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/4210966375978937471',
    'link2' => '2015/05/what-your-business-can-learn-from',
    'article' => '<p>Cirque du Soleil and other businesses with completely new business models deliver customer value in a different way. Cirque du Soleil re-invented the concept of a "Circus" by providing its customers with more of what they really wanted - the element of performance and excitement, coupled with an air of exclusivity - which allowed it to access a new and higher spending audience base.</p>
<p>Cirque removed costly performers, who in the classic circus environment were stars in their own right, and with their own brand. These were replaced with performers who were part of a group and who were interchangeable, hugely increasing the flexibility of the business and ability to roll out the same experience in different locations, by hiring and training performers locally, thus saving on the cost of moving people and equipment.</p>
<p>They also removed costly animals, which create huge overheads in respect to animal welfare. The element of excitement that animals traditionally provided was replaced with daring performances and elaborate choreography.</p>
<p>Cirque du Soleil seems like a unique business, but all businesses can learn from their example. The principle idea is that the business no longer competes in a like-for-like comparison with its peers, but instead stands out by introducing unique selling points, that other businesses cannot reproduce or that is hard to quantify. Making a business unique and its services special, is always a good thing. If this can be coupled with a way of reducing costs, a business can leap ahead of its competitors and hugely increase its customer base.</p>
<p>If there is anything I can do to help, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a> to discuss your ideas.</p>',
    'labels' => 'advantages, advice, business, competition, uniqueness',
  ),
  15 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1431586800,
    'title' => 'Easy steps to avoid stupid passwords',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/6274423694891209059',
    'link2' => '2015/05/easy-steps-to-avoid-stupid-passwords',
    'article' => '<p>Don’t be a victim of easy-to-guess, simple - or stupid - passwords.</p>
<p>Fist of all you have to acknowledge that you have a password problem. Many people have stupid passwords. Survey after survey proves that over half of passwords in use can be hacked within a few minutes.</p>
<p>The top 25 most common passwords from 2014 are:</p>
<ol><li>123456</li><li>password</li><li>12345</li><li>12345678</li><li>qwerty</li><li>123456789</li><li>1234</li><li>baseball</li><li>dragon</li><li>football</li><li>1234567</li><li>monkey</li><li>letmein</li><li>abc123</li><li>111111</li><li>mustang</li><li>access</li><li>shadow</li><li>master</li><li>michael</li><li>superman</li><li>696969</li><li>123123</li><li>batman</li><li>trustno1</li></ol>
<p>(Source: Gizmodo - <a href="http://gizmodo.com/the-25-most-popular-passwords-of-2014-were-all-doomed-1680596951">http://gizmodo.com/the-25-most-popular-passwords-of-2014-were-all-doomed-1680596951</a>)</p>
<p>Is your password in the list? No? That\'s a good start, but you\'re not in the clear just yet. Even if your password isn\'t on the list, chances are it can still be hacked within a matter of weeks.</p>
<p>So, a good approach is to use a password manager to create new codes. Really good, secure passwords use long sequences of characters, numbers and special characters. There are many solutions out there, from LastPass to Dashlane to 1Password to KeePass, and they all allow you to generate good, complex passwords. They also allow you to manage these passwords securely and reduce the burden of having to type them in manually, or having to copy and paste them, by providing plug-ins for most of the popular browsers and other software so usernames and passwords are automatically completed for you.</p>
<p>However, even with a really long, complex password, it is still recommended that you have a different password for each of your online accounts. Again, the password managers mentioned above help here.</p>
<p>So there is really no excuse for simple, easy-to-guess, stupid passwords.</p>
<p>For advice on how to implement strong password and tools to help you manage your passwords, please <a href="/contact/">don\'t hesitate to contact me</a>.</p>',
    'labels' => 'passwords, protection, security',
  ),
  16 => 
  array (
    'published' => 1430982000,
    'title' => 'Build your own website! - The top 3 content management systems',
    'link' => 'http://www.blogger.com/feeds/4058815900324538230/posts/default/2758286879469941178',
    'link2' => '2015/05/top-3-cms',
    'article' => '<p>Most businesses use a web development company to host and maintain their site for them. In many cases that is a good solution, as the business can give the headache of running a website to a third-party. However, bringing the hosting of a website in-house gives the business greater control and there are now so many mature solutions available that don\'t require a full-time web developer on the payroll.</p>
<p>The solutions are called CMS - content management systems. They provide a simple way for non-web savvy staff to create professional looking pages. Staff only need to concentrate on producing great content - the CMS does the rest. The content\'s look is decided by a website template that usually can be customized to fit the business\'s brand and changing to a different template doesn\'t require the whole website to be rebuilt.</p>
<p>Many CMS are free, or open-source, but they are actively maintained, usually by a large community of developers who work on the CMS in their spare time. That means that if a bug is found in whatever CMS you choose, there will soon be a new version available that fixes the problem - and new versions also usually offer a slew of new functionality. So free isn\'t necessarily a negative, and a lot of businesses have jumped on the open-source bandwagon for a number of core business systems.</p>
<p>There are also a number of hosting solutions available for any of these CMS, so if web hosting is an issue for the business, a third-party supplier can easily be found.</p>
<p>Here’s a look at three of the most widely-used CMS - Wordpress, Drupal and Joomla. No solution will ever answer all business requirements, so it depends on the business goals as to what solution is the right one.</p>
<p>For a simple brochure-type site Wordpress is the best choice and it was really the first widely used open-source CMS. It is very easy to install and configure, and very easy to use. There is a huge number of plug-ins and templates available, so chances are that it will meet most business requirements.</p>
<p>Drupal on the other hand is a little harder to install and configure, and even though there is a large number of plug-ins and templates available to customize the website, Drupal\'s strength is that with some development knowledge it can be extended to do exactly what the business wants. However, that does mean the business needs to either find a developer to work in-house or to go to an external web development company for help.</p>
<p>Joomla is the middle ground between Wordpress and Drupal. It does offer a fair bit of customization by a developer, but it already does a great deal out of the box, is easily to install and configure, and there is a large number of plug-ins and templates available to make the website fit the business brand and requirements.</p>
<p>Below is a chart offering a detailed view of the pros and cons of the three solutions.</p>
